 MVC Flow in Spring (Detailed)
Let’s walk through the complete request lifecycle in a Spring MVC application:
1. Client Sends Request
•	A user sends an HTTP request (e.g., GET /products).
2. Front Controller: DispatcherServlet
•	Spring Boot automatically registers a DispatcherServlet.
•	It acts as the Front Controller: the single entry point for all incoming requests.
3. Handler Mapping
•	DispatcherServlet consults HandlerMapping to find the appropriate Controller method.
•	It uses annotations like @RequestMapping, @GetMapping, etc., to match the URL and HTTP method.
4. Controller (Request Handler)
•	The matched controller method (also called a request handler) is invoked.
•	It processes the request, interacts with the Model, and returns a ModelAndView or data (in REST APIs).
5. View Resolver
•	If a view name is returned, the ViewResolver resolves it to an actual view (e.g., a Thymeleaf or JSP file).
•	In REST APIs, the response is serialized to JSON or XML.
6. Response Sent to Client
•	The final response (HTML or JSON) is sent back to the client.

🌱 What is Spring?
Spring is an open-source framework created to simplify Java development.
Instead of writing a lot of repetitive code to handle things like connecting to databases, managing security, or handling web requests, Spring takes care of that for you.
Key Features:
•	Dependency Injection (DI): Promotes loose coupling by injecting dependencies at runtime.
•	Aspect-Oriented Programming (AOP): Separates cross-cutting concerns (like logging, security).
•	Transaction Management: Declarative transaction handling.
•	Integration with other frameworks: Hibernate, JPA, JMS, etc.
•	Modular Architecture: You can use only what you need.


